CALL FOR APPLICATIONS FOR ADMISSION
TO THE M.A. PROGRAM IN OTTOMAN HISTORY
Application period
The M.A. Program in Ottoman History, which is organized by the Department
of History and Archaeology of the University of Crete in collaboration with the
Institute for Mediterranean Studies/FORTH, invites applications from
prospective students. Applications, along with all the supporting documents
described below, are to be submitted online from Monday, March 16, until
Monday, April 27, 2026. “Ottoman History” is a two-year M.A. Program that
leads to the award of a Master’s Degree in Ottoman History.
Application submission – Required supporting documents
Applications and all supporting documents may be submitted ONLY online at
https://postgrad.cict.uoc.gr. Applicants must create a user account, fill in the
application form, upload the required supporting documents (as pdf files with
a maximum file size of 2MB each and a maximum file size of 20MB in total),
and finalize their applications by the deadline for applications.
The required supporting documents are as follows:
1. Copy of B.A. degree or official letter confirming completion of
undergraduate studies (Final-year students expecting to graduate by
September 2026: please see the information under “Eligibility to apply”
below).
2. Official transcript of undergraduate studies, including all courses and
grades, as well as the applicant’s final graduation grade.
3. Detailed CV.
4. Copies of foreign language certificates (minimum requirement:
knowledge of English at B2 level according to the Common European
Framework of Reference for Languages).
5. Written research proposal (approx. 2-3 pages) on a topic in Ottoman
history with a clear research question, methodological approach, and relevant
bibliography.
6. Sample of written work (B.A. thesis or one [1] seminar essay).
7. Proof of identity (passport or identity card).
8. Any other document that the applicant may consider relevant.
Each supporting document must be in a single pdf file. Partial
document scans or photographs of documents will not be accepted.
Supporting documents do not need to be certified. However, they must be
complete, clear and legible. The Secretariat of the Department of History and
Archaeology will verify the authenticity of the documents submitted by
successful applicants. In this context, applicants admitted to the Program who
hold B.A. degrees and transcripts from non-Greek universities will be asked to
submit these documents with certification of the authenticity of the signatures
in accordance with the Hague Convention (Apostille). For documents issued
in countries where the Hague Convention does not apply, successful
applicants must request that the University that issued the documents send
them directly from an official institutional email address to history-
archaeology@ia.uoc.gr, so that the Secretariat of the Department of History
and Archaeology can verify them against the copies submitted by the
applicants.
In addition, applicants must arrange for at least two (2) university
professors who are familiar with their academic abilities and personal qualities
to submit letters of reference about them. The letters should be sent directly
from the referees’ institutional email addresses to history-
archaeology@ia.uoc.gr. Letters of reference from members of the
Admissions Committee will not be accepted.
Languages of admission applications
Admission applications may be submitted in English or Greek. The B.A. thesis
or seminar essay must be submitted in English, Greek, Turkish, or French.
2
Eligibility to apply
Applicants are required to hold a B.A. degree from a university department or
program in the Humanities or Social Sciences. Applications from holders of
other B.A. degrees may be accepted at the discretion of the Admissions
Committee only if their undergraduate studies are relevant to Ottoman History
or if they have successfully completed a sufficient number of courses in
Ottoman history.
Holders of B.A. degrees from non-Greek universities who possess a
degree equivalence certificate from the competent national recognition
authority (Hellenic NARIC – DOATAP) are required to submit it with their
application. Otherwise, they must verify whether their university and degree
are listed in the National Registry of Foreign Recognized Higher
Education Institutions and the National Registry of Foreign Recognized
Academic Title Types. If not, applicants are advised to contact the Graduate
Secretary of the Department of History and Archaeology, Ms. Anastasia
Tzanoudaki, tel. (+30)2831077379, email history-archaeology@ia.uoc.gr,
before applying.
Final-year students expecting to graduate by September 2026 are
welcome to apply for admission to the M.A. Program in Ottoman History. They
are required to submit an academic transcript and, if available, an official letter
confirming completion of their B.A. studies. If admitted to the Program, they
will be required to present their B.A. degree upon graduation.
Admission process – Admissions Committee
The supporting documents submitted with each application for admission to
the M.A. Program in Ottoman History will be evaluated by the Admissions
Committee, which will also conduct interviews with the applicants.
The Admissions Committee is composed of Professor Antonis
Anastasopoulos (chair), Research Director Marinos Sariyannis, and Principal
Researcher Yannis Spyropoulos.
Selection criteria
The selection criteria for admission to the M.A. Program in Ottoman History
are as follows:
3
1. B.A. degree (multiplier: 1). For degrees from non-Greek academic
institutions, the degree grade will be converted to a 10-point scale (1-10). For
final-year students, their grade-point average (GPA) at the time of application
for admission to the M.A. Program in Ottoman History will be taken as the
degree grade.
2. Evaluation of the submitted B.A. thesis or seminar essay by the
Admissions Committee (multiplier: 2).
3. Evaluation of the letters of reference by the Admissions Committee
(multiplier: 1).
4. Evaluation by the Admissions Committee of the applicant’s competence in
languages other than their native language (multiplier: 1).
5. Evaluation of the applicant’s research proposal by the Admissions
Committee (multiplier: 1.5).
6. Evaluation of the applicant’s oral interview by the Admissions Committee
(multiplier: 2). Any research or professional experience relevant to Ottoman
history, as well as other pertinent information in the applicant’s CV, will be
positively considered during the interview.
All of the above will be scored on a ten-point scale.
To be admitted, applicants must achieve a pass mark (5 out of 10) in
each of the six fields listed above (1-6) and obtain a total score of at least 60
out of 85.
Interviews
The Admissions Committee will invite all applicants to an interview, either in
person in Rethymno or online. Interviews will be conducted in English from
May 4 to May 11, 2026. Each applicant will be notified individually by the
Secretariat of the Department of History and Archaeology via email of the
exact date, time, and mode of their interview (in person or online).
Part of the interview will require applicants to answer questions on the
history and institutions of the Ottoman Empire. The Admissions
Committee recommends the following indicative bibliography:
1) Caroline Finkel, Osman’s Dream: The Story of the Ottoman Empire,
1300-1923, London: John Murray, 2005
2) Douglas A. Howard, A History of the Ottoman Empire, Cambridge:
4
Cambridge University Press, 2017
3) Donald Quataert, The Ottoman Empire, 1700-1922, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press, 2000
Date of announcement of provisional results
The provisional results of the admissions procedure for the M.A. Program in
Ottoman History will be communicated to applicants by email on Friday, May
15, 2026.
